    <title>Combined summary - Algorithm Agility for Bitcoin to maintain security in the face of quantum and classic breaks in the signature algorithms</title>
    <updated>2026-02-20T03:42:51.796521+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CAEM=y+US1-QRgAXStAZ2tsJiPBeQtm7=_q7LrQdDHR=VAci+vA@mail.gmail.com/T/#m872dbe4ab7306d6de1de50301f596cd15c0f07ae" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-02-09 14:20:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The conversation delves into the resilience and adaptability of Bitcoin's cryptographic mechanisms amid concerns over quantum computing threats and the obsolescence of certain cryptographic primitives. The discussion points out that while Bitcoin still employs OP_SHA1 within its Script and TapScript, despite known SHA-1 collisions, the use of MD5 remains unbroken in terms of preimage attacks, illustrating a nuanced perspective on what constitutes a &quot;break&quot; in cryptographic terms. This distinction emphasizes the complexity of cryptographic security and the challenges in determining when to phase out older cryptographic elements from the Bitcoin protocol.
Further exploration in the dialogue highlights the robustness of Bitcoin's current signature scheme, which relies on both the secp256k1 elliptic curve and SHA-256 hashing algorithm. The argument presented is that compromising only one component of this dual requirement—specifically, the secp256k1 curve—would not entirely negate the security of Bitcoin transactions due to the persistence of secure hash functions like SHA-256. This underlines the layered defenses within Bitcoin's design, ensuring that multiple barriers exist against potential cryptographic vulnerabilities.
Moreover, the discussion touches upon the theoretical possibility of enforcing specific proof-of-work requirements on transaction signatures through the use of Script operations like OP_SIZE, even in scenarios where the elliptic curve cryptography might be weakened. This suggests that even with advancements in quantum computing, mechanisms could be in place to maintain some level of security and functionality within the Bitcoin network.
Notably, the conversation also addresses the broader implications of maintaining or disabling older cryptographic functions within Bitcoin's codebase, acknowledging the inertia and complexities involved in evolving the protocol in response to emerging cryptographic research and threats. It reflects ongoing debates within the Bitcoin development community about balancing innovation with the preservation of Bitcoin's foundational principles and operational integrity.</summary>
